// UNSHADOW 🔵 C — refinement-type tag-check elision micro-bench.
//
// Hot loop hitting the unary-plus numeric-operand tag-check on a provably-int
// literal (`+1`). With the codegen elision OFF, each iteration emits a runtime
// statement-expr guard `if (!(HX_IS_INT||HX_IS_FLOAT||TAG_CHAR)) hexa_throw(...)`.
// With elision ON, the guard is DELETED (the literal is statically TAG_INT, so
// the throw arm is unreachable dead code — unary + is numeric identity).
//
// Build A/B with two transpilers (hexat.base = origin/main codegen,
// hexat.new = elision codegen) linked to the SAME runtime.o, then byte-diff
// stdout (must be IDENTICAL) and time the loop.
//
// FINDING (mini macOS arm64, clang -O2): base/new produce BYTE-IDENTICAL
// assembly — clang -O2 already dead-eliminates the literal-tag guard via
// constant propagation on the {.tag=TAG_INT} compound literal. Source-level
// elision is REDUNDANT with -O2 (perf closed-negative); correctness is proven
// lossless (byte-identical output). See .verdicts/unshadow-C-tag-elision/.
fn main() {
    let mut sum = 0
    let mut i = 0
    while i < 60000000 {
        sum = sum + (+1)
        i = i + 1
    }
    println(to_string(sum))
}
